IMPORTANT — READ THIS ENTIRE AGREEMENT BEFORE ACCESSING, READING, CLONING,
RUNNING, OR OTHERWISE INTERACTING WITH THE PLANIT WATCHDOG SERVICE OR ANY
PORTION OF ITS SOURCE CODE, CONFIGURATION, OR OPERATIONAL DATA.

This License Agreement ("Agreement") is a legally binding contract between You
and Aakshat Hariharan ("Author") governing Your access to and use of the PlanIt
Watchdog Service — the autonomous infrastructure health monitoring, incident
management, uptime tracking, and alerting daemon that provides operational
intelligence for the PlanIt platform.

The Watchdog Service is not a generic monitoring tool. It is purpose-built for
the PlanIt infrastructure, containing proprietary incident detection heuristics,
alert suppression logic, uptime aggregation algorithms, and integration-specific
configurations for ntfy.sh, Discord webhooks, and the PlanIt-specific health
response schema. These constitute trade secrets and copyrighted works of the
Author.

================================================================================
SECTION 1 — DEFINITIONS
================================================================================

1.1   "Watchdog Service" or "Software" means the PlanIt autonomous monitoring
      daemon in its entirety, including without limitation:

      (a)  All source code implementing the health-check polling engine,
           including the polling intervals, endpoint selection, response
           interpretation logic, and liveness determination algorithms;

      (b)  The incident lifecycle management system, including incident
           detection thresholds, auto-resolution logic, severity classification,
           consecutive-failure counting, and incident state machine
           implementation;

      (c)  The alert routing and deduplication system, including the ntfy.sh
           push notification integration, the Discord webhook integration,
           the alert suppression and cooldown logic, and the notification
           priority scheme;

      (d)  The uptime history aggregation system, including the rolling window
           calculations, the percentage computation methodology, the bucketing
           strategy, and the data retention policy;

      (e)  The service dependency graph and check schedule, including the list
           of monitored services, their check frequencies, their timeout
           thresholds, and the ordering of checks;

      (f)  The PlanIt-specific health response parsing logic, including the
           interpretation of backend alive/dead states, the Router Service
           health aggregation, and the watchdog status API response format;

      (g)  The mesh-authenticated self-reporting endpoints, including the
           /watchdog/ping and /watchdog/status endpoints and their
           authentication mechanisms;

      (h)  All configuration files, environment variable schemas, deployment
           manifests, and operational documentation associated with the
           Watchdog Service;

      (i)  All code comments, architectural notes, operational procedures,
           and runbooks embedded in or accompanying the Watchdog Service.

1.2   "Author" means Aakshat Hariharan, the sole designer, developer, and
      intellectual property owner of the Watchdog Service and all proprietary
      systems, algorithms, and configurations embodied therein.

1.3   "You" or "Licensee" means any individual, site reliability engineer,
      DevOps practitioner, organization, company, or other legal or natural
      person that in any way reads, accesses, downloads, clones, executes,
      deploys, or otherwise interacts with the Watchdog Service or any file
      or component thereof.

1.4   "Monitoring Intelligence" means the proprietary collection of heuristics,
      thresholds, timing parameters, and decision logic embedded in the Watchdog
      Service that govern how it detects incidents, determines severity, routes
      alerts, suppresses duplicates, and tracks uptime — all of which constitute
      trade secrets of the Author.

1.5   "Operational Data" means the uptime history records, incident logs, alert
      histories, and performance metrics generated by the Watchdog Service during
      its operation, which constitute proprietary data owned by the Author.

1.6   "Hosted Infrastructure" means the production deployment of the Watchdog
      Service operated by the Author, monitoring the PlanIt platform in real-time.

1.7   "Derivative Work" means any monitoring tool, daemon, script, service, or
      other software work that is derived from, copies, adapts, or reimplements
      any portion of the Watchdog Service's Monitoring Intelligence, incident
      management logic, or alert routing system.

1.8   "Deploy" means to execute, run, host, or otherwise operate the Watchdog
      Service or any portion thereof on any computing infrastructure.

1.9   "Commercial Use" means any use of the Watchdog Service or any Derivative
      Work in connection with any revenue-generating commercial activity.

